SIMPLE: slur
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slur
<hw>Slur</hw> <pr>(sl⟦ucir⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Slurred</conjf> <pr>(sl⟦ucir⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr.
& vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Slurring</conjf>
<pr>(sl⟦ucir⟧r"r⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. OE. <ets>sloor</ets>
mud, clay, Icel. <ets>sl⟦omac⟧ra</ets>, <ets>slo⟦edh⟧ra</ets>, to trail
or drag one's self along, D. <ets>sleuren</ets>, <ets>sloren</ets>, to
train, to drag, to do negligently and slovenly, D. <ets>sloor</ets>,
<ets>sloerie</ets>, a sluttish girl.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To soil; to
sully; to contaminate; to disgrace.</def>
<rj><au>Cudworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disparage; to traduce.</def>
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cover over; to disguise; to conceal; to pass over
lightly or with little notice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With periods, points, and tropes, he <qex>slurs</qex> his
crimes.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cheat, as by sliding a die; to trick.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>slur</qex> men of what they fought for.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To pronounce indistinctly; <as>as, to <ex>slur</ex>
syllables; to <ex>slur</ex> one's words</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To sing or perform in a smooth,
gliding style; to connect smoothly in performing, as several notes or
tones.</def> <rj><au>Busby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>To blur or double, as an
impression from type; to mackle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slur</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slur
<hw>Slur</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A mark or stain; hence, a
slight reproach or disgrace; a stigma; a reproachful intimation; an
innuendo.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Gaining to his name a lasting
<xex>slur</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A trick played upon a person; an imposition.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A mark, thus [⟦upslur⟧ or
⟦downslur⟧], connecting notes that are to be sung to the same syllable,
or made in one continued breath of a wind instrument, or with one stroke
of a bow; a tie; a sign of legato.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In knitting machines, a contrivance for depressing
the sinkers successively by passing over them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slurred</ent>⟦br⟧
